Content: :ibox:THIS QUESTION HAS TWO PARTS.
Read the sentence from paragraph 1.
:box:Rufus sat beside me for a while, hoping I'd be up to something more than misery.
What does the word MISERY mean as it is used in the sentence?

A.Choice: confusion

B.Choice: exhaustion

C.Choice: nervousness

D.Choice: unhappiness

Content: Which detail from the story provides the BEST clue for the meaning of the word MISERY?

A.Choice: “... waiting for nothing, with nothing I wanted to do.”

B.Choice: “... tired of waiting and went off on his own ...”

C.Choice: “And right away, I knew what I had to do.”

D.Choice: “No plans.”

Content: :ibox:THIS QUESTION HAS TWO PARTS.
How does the narrator's apology to the neighbors contribute to the theme of the story?

A.Choice: It shows that feelings of guilt will pass.

B.Choice: It shows that it is best to admit to mistakes.

C.Choice: It shows that it is difficult to understand how other people are feeling.

D.Choice: It shows that it requires bravery to approach others who are angry.

Content: Which detail from the story BEST supports the answer to Part A?

A.Choice: “Yes, they might ambush me ...”

B.Choice: “... because I was going to do the right thing.”

C.Choice: “... I got to the property line without harm ...”

D.Choice: “Like my heart was heavier and lighter ...”

Content: :ibox:THIS QUESTION HAS TWO PARTS.
In the passage from Ida B, how are the narrator and Claire similar?

A.Choice: They both dislike quitting something before it is finished.

B.Choice: Neither of them is good at apologizing when they are wrong.

C.Choice: They are both unsure about what the other person will do.

D.Choice: Neither of them is comfortable with being neighbors.

Content: Choose ONE detail for the narrator and ONE detail for Claire that support the comparison in Part A.

A.Choice: “Yes, they might ambush me, and I might not come back in one piece.” (paragraph 5)

B.Choice: “I stopped just before I stepped onto the land that now belonged to the DeLunas ...” (paragraph 6)

C.Choice: “And there was Claire straight ahead, looking at me, waiting for me.” (paragraph 7)

D.Choice: “'I'm sorry I scared you in the woods. I'm sorry I was mean to you.'” (paragraph 10)

E.Choice: “Should I tell her about Mama and the trees and school and everything?” (paragraph 10)

F.Choice: “... you have to do the whole house or you're tracking dirt from one place to the other.” (paragraph 21)

Content: :ibox:THIS QUESTION HAS TWO PARTS.
What does the phrase few and far between mean as it is used in paragraph 2?

A.Choice: less often

B.Choice: less happy

C.Choice: more distant

D.Choice: harder to hear

Content: Which detail from the story of the passage helps the reader understand the meaning of the phrase FEW AND FAR BETWEEN?

A.Choice: “... does his best talking in stories ...”

B.Choice: “So on the occasion ...”

C.Choice: “'... did I ever tell you ...'”

D.Choice: “... where he'd lived once upon a time.”

Content: :ibox:THIS QUESTION HAS TWO PARTS.
Which pair of sentences provides the BEST summary of the story from Moon Over Manifest?

A.Choice: A girl wonders about a town she will see for the first time. She decides to jump off the train to see it sooner.

B.Choice: A girl lives with her father but must go on a train alone. Her father is upset because she had gotten very sick.

C.Choice: A girl rides a train alone to go live in her father's hometown. She misses her father but is curious about her new home.

D.Choice: A girl enjoys a train ride to a new home. She looks through the things she has brought with her and thinks about the past.

Content: Which TWO sentences from the story BEST support the answer to Part A?

A.Choice: “Maybe that was how I found comfort then, even with him being so far away.”

B.Choice: “It started the day I got a cut on my knee.”

C.Choice: “I reached into my satchel for the flour sack that held my few special things.”

D.Choice: “In a gold case, it wore like a pocket watch, but inside was a compass showing every direction.”

E.Choice: “But as anyone worth his salt knows, it's best to get a look at a place before it gets a look at you.”

F.Choice: “Finally, I saw a grassy spot and jumped.”

Content: :ibox:THIS QUESTION HAS TWO PARTS.
In the story from Moon Over Manifest, how do paragraphs 2 and 3 contribute to the overall structure of the story?

A.Choice: They compare the personalities of two characters.

B.Choice: They describe the setting where the story takes place.

C.Choice: They present a solution to the main conflict in the story.

D.Choice: They establish the problem of the story.

Content: Which detail from the story BEST supports the answer to Part A?

A.Choice: “... I could taste the sadness in his voice when he told me I couldn't stay with him ...”

B.Choice: “... while he worked a railroad job back in Iowa.”

C.Choice: “The doctors said I was lucky to come out of it.”

D.Choice: “... a letter from Gideon telling folks that I would be received by Pastor Howard at the Manifest depot ...”

Content: The passages from Ida B and Moon Over Manifest both include events that did not happen exactly how the narrators expected them to happen. Write an essay describing how each narrator's point of view influences how these events are described. Be sure to use details from BOTH stories.
:ibox:THIS QUESTION HAS TWO PARTS.
Read the sentence from paragraph 7 of the passage.
:box:Gwen followed the Principal with her head in a buzzing whirl.
What is the meaning of the phrase IN A BUZZING WHIRL as it is used in the sentence?

A.Choice: many thoughts happening at once

B.Choice: a lot of confusing information

C.Choice: many challenging activities

D.Choice: a lot of daydreaming

Content: Which detail in paragraph 7 helps the reader understand the meaning of IN A BUZZING WHIRL?

A.Choice: “... seemed like a dream to be suddenly translated ...”

B.Choice: “... had a little time to get accustomed to the idea ...”

C.Choice: “... have liked a day's preparation ...”

D.Choice: “... change over and discuss it at home.”

Content: :ibox:THIS QUESTION HAS TWO PARTS.
Which statement BEST describes the main difference between Gwen and Miss Roscoe in the passage from The Youngest Girl in the Fifth?

A.Choice: Gwen takes time to think while Miss Roscoe acts quickly.

B.Choice: Gwen seems to be timid while Miss Roscoe appears to be daring.

C.Choice: Gwen likes to dream while Miss Roscoe deals with facts.

D.Choice: Gwen wants things to remain the same while Miss Roscoe seeks change.

Content: Which TWO details from the passage support the answer to Part A?

A.Choice: “... quailed alike under the glance of her keen dark eyes.” (paragraph 1)

B.Choice: “... stood hesitating near the door.” (paragraph 2)

C.Choice: “'... you ought to be able to manage the work ...'” (paragraph 2)

D.Choice: “'With that help you shouldn't be so far behind.'” (paragraph 4)

E.Choice: “... wished she could have had a little time to get accustomed ...” (paragraph 7)

F.Choice: “... she never had a moment to waste ...” (paragraph 7)

Content: :ibox:THIS QUESTION HAS TWO PARTS.
How does the narrator's point of view influence how the events are described?

A.Choice: By focusing on Gwen's reactions to the events, the narrator creates sympathy for her situation.

B.Choice: By including only Miss Roscoe's dialogue during the events, the narrator highlights her power.

C.Choice: By including the students' reactions to Miss Roscoe during the events, the narrator provides information about other characters.

D.Choice: By focusing events on Gwen's feelings about wanting more time to make her decision, the narrator shows she has trouble making decisions.

Content: Which detail from the passage supports the answer in Part A?

A.Choice: “... quailed alike under the glance of her keen dark eyes.” (paragraph 1)

B.Choice: “... stared at Miss Roscoe, too surprised to answer.” (paragraph 3)

C.Choice: “'... should be very sorry to have to put you down again.'” (paragraph 6)

D.Choice: “It seemed like a dream ...” (paragraph 7)

Content: :ibox:THIS QUESTION HAS TWO PARTS.
How do paragraphs 2 and 3 help provide the overall structure of the passage?

A.Choice: They describe the Principal's relationship with the students.

B.Choice: They explain how the students feel about the Principal.

C.Choice: They show how quickly the Principal acts on her decision.

D.Choice: They reveal the Principal's plan to assist struggling students.

Content: Which TWO details from paragraphs 6–7 of the passage BEST support the answer to Part A?

A.Choice: “'... you must try your best.'”

B.Choice: “'I shall trust you to make a great effort.'”

C.Choice: “'I should be very sorry to have to put you ...'”

D.Choice: “'Come with me now, and I'll take you ...'”

E.Choice: “... time to get accustomed to the idea ...”

F.Choice: “... always did things in a hurry ...”

Content: :ibox:THIS QUESTION HAS TWO PARTS.
What are TWO main ideas of the article by Lauren Tarshis?

A.Choice: Oil spills can spread quickly.

B.Choice: Penguins are good swimmers.

C.Choice: Oil spills are a great threat to penguins.

D.Choice: Penguins take good care of their young.

E.Choice: Penguins are interesting animals to watch.

F.Choice: People work hard to help the penguins get better.

Content: Which TWO sentences from the article BEST support the answer to Part A?

A.Choice: “Others cuddle with their mates and dote on their chicks.”

B.Choice: “As you plunge into the sea, your wings become powerful underwater propellers.”

C.Choice: “You are not the only penguin that has become soaked with the poisonous oil.”

D.Choice: “The impact of oil on a penguin (or any bird) is immediate and devastating.”

E.Choice: “In the wild, penguins hunt for sardines and gobble them up while they are still alive and wriggling.”

F.Choice: “All of them have one thing in common: a mission to save as many penguins as possible.”

Content: :ibox:THIS QUESTION HAS TWO PARTS.
Read the sentence from paragraph 5 of the article by Dyan deNapoli.
:box:Normally, African penguins are vocal birds.
What does the word VOCAL mean as it is used in the sentence?

A.Choice: shy

B.Choice: fearful

C.Choice: noisy

D.Choice: challenging

Content: Which sentence from the article BEST helps the reader understand the meaning of VOCAL in Part A?

A.Choice: “I expected to walk into a chorus of honking and squawking.”

B.Choice: “Only the hushed voices of people could be heard.”

C.Choice: “I felt overwhelmed.”

D.Choice: “My heart ached for the distressed birds.”

Content: :ibox:THIS QUESTION HAS TWO PARTS.
Select the BEST summary of the article by Dyan deNapoli.

A.Choice: A large oil spill in the water near Cape Town endangered the lives of a nearby penguin population. Despite their efforts, rescuers quickly realized that the penguins needed more care than they could provide.

B.Choice: A large oil spill in the water near Cape Town threatened the penguins who lived on a nearby island. Experts spent months caring for the injured birds, but many were unable to be released back into the wild.

C.Choice: A large oil spill in the water near Cape Town placed a nearby penguin population in danger. Thousands of rescuers worked together to help the penguins and eventually returned them to their home.

D.Choice: A large oil spill in the water near Cape Town threatened the lives of penguins living nearby. Experts trained many people who volunteered to help the penguins.

Content: Which TWO quotations from the article BEST support the answer to Part A?

A.Choice: “The region's penguins were in trouble.”

B.Choice: “The center needed penguin keepers to train the volunteers.”

C.Choice: “But we already had our hands full with 20,000 recovering birds.”

D.Choice: “If any more birds were oiled, we wouldn't have enough resources to save them.”

E.Choice: “In the end, more than 90 percent of the oiled penguins were successfully returned to the wild.”

F.Choice: “In a previous large-scale penguin rescue, only half of the oiled birds survived.”

Content: :ibox:THIS QUESTION HAS TWO PARTS.
How does the author, Dyan deNapoli, support the idea that cleaning the penguins was a difficult task?

A.Choice: by providing a comparison of two ways to clean penguins

B.Choice: by providing a description of the steps for cleaning penguins

C.Choice: by providing a quotation from someone who cleaned penguins

D.Choice: by providing an explanation of why oil must be cleaned from penguins

Content: Which paragraph in the article by Dyan deNapoli BEST supports the answer to Part A?

A.Choice: paragraph 1

B.Choice: paragraph 6

C.Choice: paragraph 7

D.Choice: paragraph 9

Content: :ibox:THIS QUESTION HAS TWO PARTS.
Which sentence BEST states a difference between how information is presented in the article by Lauren Tarshis and how information is presented in the article by Dyan deNapoli?

A.Choice: The article by Tarshis puts the reader in the role of a penguin affected by an oil spill event, while the article by deNapoli tells how a person was affected by an oil spill event.

B.Choice: The article by Tarshis focuses on statistics to provide more information about an oil spill event, while the article by deNapoli shares the emotional effects on rescuers after an oil spill event.

C.Choice: The article by Tarshis tells about the cause of an oil spill event, while the article by deNapoli highlights the process used to clean the penguins affected by an oil spill event.

D.Choice: The article by Tarshis offers details about the experience of the rescuers who assist after an oil spill event, while the article by deNapoli discusses the causes of an oil spill event.

Content: Select TWO details from the articles that support the answer to Part A. Select one detail from the article by Lauren Tarshis and one detail from the article by Dyan deNapoli.

A.Choice: “As it sank, 1,300 tons of toxic crude oil gushed into the sea.” (from the article by Tarshis)

B.Choice: “You are not the only penguin that has become soaked with the poisonous oil.” (from the article by Tarshis)

C.Choice: “And they intend to save every single one.” (from the article by Tarshis)

D.Choice: “I was about to take part in what would become the largest animal rescue operation ever attempted.” (from the article by deNapoli)

E.Choice: “The rescuers had set up makeshift pools, which held about 100 oiled birds each.” (from the article by deNapoli)

F.Choice: “It takes two people—one to hold the penguin, another to do the washing.” (from the article by deNapoli)

Content: Answer Part A and Part B for this question.
Which phrase BEST describes both the workers in the article by Lauren Tarshis and the volunteers in the article by Dyan deNapoli?

A.Choice: ready to save as many birds as possible

B.Choice: concerned about slipping on the oil-slick rocks

C.Choice: hopeful that more rescuers will arrive to help

D.Choice: angry because of the carelessness of humans

Content: Select ONE detail from the article by Lauren Tarshis and ONE detail from the article by Dyan deNapoli that BEST support the answer to Part A.

A.Choice: “These men and women know what you don't: that this oil spill is a catastrophe for you and your species.” (article by Lauren Tarshis)

B.Choice: “The sight of all of these scared and injured penguins is heartbreaking to the humans.” (article by Lauren Tarshis)

C.Choice: “As news of the rescue effort spreads, hundreds, and then thousands, of volunteers flock to the warehouse, eager to help.” (article by Lauren Tarshis)

D.Choice: “Volunteers were showing up by the thousands, but they had no experience.” (article by Dyan deNapoli)

E.Choice: “But we already had our hands full with 20,000 recovering birds.” (article by Dyan deNapoli)

F.Choice: “As the Penguin Lady, I'm used to facing such hazards to care for the animals I love.” (article by Dyan deNapoli)

Content: :ibox:THIS QUESTION HAS TWO PARTS.
What is the meaning of INGESTION as it is used in paragraph 9 of the article “Update on Penguin Rescue Efforts from Oil Spill in South Atlantic”?

A.Choice: removing from a protective covering

B.Choice: taking something into the body

C.Choice: working hard at a difficult task

D.Choice: sticking tightly to a surface

Content: Which phrase from paragraph 9 helps the reader understand the meaning of INGESTION?

A.Choice: “Treat the affected animals as quickly as possible ...”

B.Choice: “... washing the feathers with detergent ...”

C.Choice: “It is a labor of love ...”

D.Choice: “... to drink fluids, vitamins and charcoal ...”

Content: :ibox:THIS QUESTION HAS TWO PARTS.

Which statement BEST describes a major difference between the structure of the articles “The Amazing Penguin Rescue” by Dyan deNapoli and “Update on Penguin Rescue Efforts from Oil Spill in South Atlantic”?

A.Choice: “Update on Penguin Rescue Efforts from Oil Spill in South Atlantic” compares and contrasts many ways people can help rescue penguins, while the article by deNapoli focuses on only one part of the rescue process.

B.Choice: “Update on Penguin Rescue Efforts from Oil Spill in South Atlantic” is mainly a chronological account of the oil spill itself, while the article by deNapoli focuses on the causes and effects of the oil spill.

C.Choice: “Update on Penguin Rescue Efforts from Oil Spill in South Atlantic” presents facts to support an argument in favor of helping penguins, while the article by deNapoli is focused mostly on opinion and emotions related to the oil spill.

D.Choice: “Update on Penguin Rescue Efforts from Oil Spill in South Atlantic” provides the main steps in the process of the rescue effort, while the article by deNapoli is a firsthand account of one person's experience.

Content: Choose TWO pieces of evidence, one from each article, that support the answer in Part A.

A.Choice: “The cargo ship MV Treasure had sunk off the coast of Cape Town, creating an oil spill.” (“The Amazing Penguin Rescue” by Dyan deNapoli)

B.Choice: “The rescuers had set up makeshift pools, which held about 100 oiled birds each.” (“The Amazing Penguin Rescue” by Dyan deNapoli)

C.Choice: “But for me, the most inspiring part was the work of the volunteers.” (“The Amazing Penguin Rescue” by Dyan deNapoli)

D.Choice: “The penguins attracted the most attention as they are critically endangered.” (“Update on Penguin Rescue Efforts from Oil Spill in South Atlantic”)

E.Choice: “The crew members were brought to the Edinburgh, which was small enough to dock on the island.” (“Update on Penguin Rescue Efforts from Oil Spill in South Atlantic”)

F.Choice: “There are four major tasks required to save the penguin colony and other affected wildlife.” (“Update on Penguin Rescue Efforts from Oil Spill in South Atlantic”)

Content: You have read three articles about penguin rescue efforts after an oil spill.

:ibox:• from “The Amazing Penguin Rescue” by Lauren Tarshis

• “The Amazing Penguin Rescue” by Dyan deNapoli

• “Update on Penguin Rescue Efforts from Oil Spill in South Atlantic”
Write an essay explaining the similarities and differences in each article's point of view about penguin rescue efforts after an oil spill. Support your essay with information from all THREE sources.
:ibox:THIS QUESTION HAS TWO PARTS.
Which statement explains how Paul responds to Johnny's challenge of turning a seed into a tree?

A.Choice: Paul is sad that Johnny misses the trees and wants him to feel better.

B.Choice: Paul is annoyed and wants to prove to Johnny that growing a tree is easy to do.

C.Choice: Paul is proud that he has cut down the trees and is surprised that Johnny is unhappy.

D.Choice: Paul is angry and wants to demonstrate to Johnny that he does not care about growing trees.

Content: Which detail from the story supports the answer to Part A?

A.Choice: “'What's so hard about growin' a tree anyway?'”

B.Choice: “Paul hems an' haws, but he sees as how he has to make good on his word.”

C.Choice: “Not wishin' to hurt any of 'em, he picks 'em up, one at a time ...”

D.Choice: “Paul is upset for a minute, then he realizes he don't need to brag to anybody ...”

Content: :ibox:THIS QUESTION HAS TWO PARTS.
At the beginning of the story, how is Johnny's view about his trees different from Paul's?

A.Choice: Johnny views his trees as food for the rabbits while Paul views them as useful in his work.

B.Choice: Johnny views his trees as the result of hard work while Paul views them as objects to win a contest.

C.Choice: Johnny views his trees as needing his protection while Paul views them as needing too much care.

D.Choice: Johnny views his trees as friends that he needs to take care of while Paul views them as something to brag about.

Content: Choose TWO details, one for Johnny and one for Paul, that support the answer to Part A.

A.Choice: “'It took you six days to plant 'em an' it took me only three days to chop 'em down.'”

B.Choice: “'It's always easier to chop somethin' down than to make it grow.'”

C.Choice: “Johnny reaches way down in the bottom o' his bag an' holds out a seed.”

D.Choice: “So he takes the little bitty seed an' pushes it down in the ground with the tip o' one fingernail.”

E.Choice: “He pats the soil around it real nice, like he seen Johnny do.”

F.Choice: “'Don't matter,' says Johnny's voice, 'if the rabbits get the seed.'”

Content: :ibox:THIS QUESTION HAS TWO PARTS.
How do paragraphs 9, 12, and 15 contribute to the overall structure of the story?

A.Choice: They include a series of events that challenge the characters.

B.Choice: They provide details that explain the importance of the setting to the characters.

C.Choice: They identify the source of the conflict between the characters.

D.Choice: They describe the process by which one of the characters learns a lesson.

Content: Which paragraph BEST supports the answer to Part A?

A.Choice: paragraph 8

B.Choice: paragraph 11

C.Choice: paragraph 14

D.Choice: paragraph 16

Content: :ibox:THIS QUESTION HAS TWO PARTS.
How does the narrator's point of view MOST influence how the events are described in the passage from “The Growin' of Paul Bunyan”?

A.Choice: It reveals Paul's actions while he cares for the seed.

B.Choice: It shows Paul's past experience with planting.

C.Choice: It shows Paul's reasons for chopping down trees.

D.Choice: It reveals Paul's relationship with Johnny.

Content: Which detail from the passage supports the answer to Part A?

A.Choice: “'It's always easier to chop somethin' down than to make it grow.'”

B.Choice: “'What's so hard about growin' a tree anyway?'”

C.Choice: “So he gets down on his knees an' he folds his hands around that little spot o' dirt an', gentle as he can, breathes his warm breath onto that tiny little seed.”

D.Choice: “Paul is upset for a minute, then he realizes he don't need to brag to anybody, that that little slip o' green is all the happiness he needs right now.”

Content: You have read a passage from “The Growin' of Paul Bunyan.” Think about how the story would be different if it were told from Johnny's point of view. Write the story from the point of view of Johnny.
:ibox:THIS QUESTION HAS TWO PARTS.
In paragraph 19 of “Phillis's Big Test,” what is the meaning of the phrase TESTIFYING TO?

A.Choice: offering

B.Choice: exhibiting

C.Choice: confirming

D.Choice: representing

Content: Which sentence from the article helps the reader understand the meaning of the phrase TESTIFYING TO as it is used in paragraph 19?

A.Choice: “She would make her own way to the public hall, where a group of men would decide once and for all: was she or was she not the author of her poems?” (paragraph 2)

B.Choice: “She had spent recent evenings copying and recopying her poetry in her own neat handwriting.” (paragraph 3)

C.Choice: “She was not content to recite her verse in drawing rooms or read one of her poems from a newspaper.” (paragraph 11)

D.Choice: “She wanted her own book, because books would not just last a lifetime; they would be there for her children and her children's children.” (paragraph 11)

Content: :ibox:THIS QUESTION HAS TWO PARTS.
According to the article “Phillis's Big Test,” which statement explains Phillis Wheatley's relationship with her master and his family?

A.Choice: They treated her as a servant.

B.Choice: They supported her as a writer.

C.Choice: They provided her with transportation.

D.Choice: They named her after a ship.

Content: Which sentence from the article provides support for the answer to Part A?

A.Choice: “ONE CRISP EARLY-AUTUMN morning in 1772, Phillis Wheatley was crossing the Boston cobblestones with a sheaf of papers held tightly under her arm.” (paragraph 1)

B.Choice: “She was just shedding her front teeth when John Wheatley bought her on the Boston docks as a servant for his wife, Susanna.” (paragraph 5)

C.Choice: “They christened their new slave Phillis, the name of the slave ship on which she arrived.” (paragraph 5)

D.Choice: “She started to turn away, but then Susanna Wheatley's words echoed in her head: Your talent will speak for itself.” (paragraph 15)

Content: :ibox:THIS QUESTION HAS TWO PARTS.
Which statement best expresses the main ideas of the article?

A.Choice: Phillis memorized her poetry by copying it, and she was fully prepared to pass her exam.

B.Choice: Phillis was grateful to her new family, and she wrote poetry to describe her experiences with them.

C.Choice: Phillis enjoyed writing poetry, and she was encouraged to publish her work.

D.Choice: Phillis was motivated by literature to express herself, and she overcame challenges to become a poet.

Content: Which TWO details from the article support the answer to Part A?

A.Choice: “She knew every line, every syllable, by heart.” (paragraph 3)

B.Choice: “She survived only by the kindness of her masters, especially the Wheatleys' twins ...” (paragraph 6)

C.Choice: “As she began to read poetry, glorious sonnets had inspired her to try her own hand at writing.” (paragraph 7)

D.Choice: “Over time she had come to appreciate her own time and place, her very own role in the chain of events ...” (paragraph 10)

E.Choice: “But she knew that she must now make the most of her opportunities.” (paragraph 10)

F.Choice: “But she must first pass this examination to make her dream come true.” (paragraph 13)

Content: :ibox:THIS QUESTION HAS TWO PARTS.
What is the difference between Phillis's audience at the Wheatley's home and the men at the exam?

A.Choice: The Wheatley audience reads her poetry before she recites it.

B.Choice: The men at the exam require her to prove herself.

C.Choice: The Wheatley audience includes highly educated people.

D.Choice: The men at the exam are greater in number.

Content: Which paragraph from “Phillis's Big Test” provides evidence to support the answer to Part A?

A.Choice: paragraph 11

B.Choice: paragraph 13

C.Choice: paragraph 14

D.Choice: paragraph 16

Content: :ibox:THIS QUESTION HAS TWO PARTS.
How does the author use evidence to support the point that Phillis was determined to succeed?

A.Choice: by showing that she stayed busy reading literature

B.Choice: by showing that she worked hard and had future plans

C.Choice: by showing that she was independent and had strong opinions

D.Choice: by showing that she received support and a good education

Content: Which TWO details from the article support the answer in Part A?

A.Choice: “... had offered her a ride to her examination, but she preferred to walk.” (paragraph 1)

B.Choice: “... could not be taken away, no matter the outcome of today.” (paragraph 3)

C.Choice: “They taught her not just English but Latin and Greek.” (paragraph 6)

D.Choice: “She had stayed up late, night after night, preparing for the examination.” (paragraph 8)

E.Choice: “She wanted her own book, because books would not just last a lifetime ...” (paragraph 11)

F.Choice: “She hurried by the bookseller's shop that she visited weekly.” (paragraph 12)

Content: :ibox:THIS QUESTION HAS TWO PARTS.
Based on information in “Phillis's Big Test,” what is the MAIN reason that Phillis works hard to pass the examination?

A.Choice: to gain fame as a poet

B.Choice: to show her skill at reciting poetry

C.Choice: to make the Wheatley family proud

D.Choice: to achieve what she thinks she is meant to do

Content: Which TWO sentences provide evidence for the answer in Part A?

A.Choice: “As she began to read poetry, glorious sonnets had inspired her to try her own hand at writing.” (paragraph 7)

B.Choice: “'Your talent will speak for itself.'” (paragraph 8)

C.Choice: “'They will discover the poet we know you to be!'” (paragraph 8)

D.Choice: “Over time she had come to appreciate her own time and place, her very own role in the chain of events stretching from past to present.” (paragraph 10)

E.Choice: “But she knew that she must now make the most of her opportunities.” (paragraph 10)
